   "trap": "Necrotising soft-tissue infection:\n- **Pain out of proportion** to skin findings — earliest/most important clue\n  - Skin can look deceptively normal early\n- Later signs: **tense oedema** beyond the erythema margin, dusky/violaceous skin, haemorrhagic **bullae**\n- **Crepitus** (gas in tissues)\n- **Skin anaesthesia** of overlying skin (cutaneous nerve infarction)\n- Systemic toxicity/shock; rapid (hourly) progression\n\nTypes:\n- **Type I** = polymicrobial (diabetics, perineum = Fournier gangrene)\n- **Type II** = group A Streptococcus +/- Staph (often healthy young, limbs)\n\nLRINEC score:\n- **Adjunct ONLY** (≥6 suspicious, ≥8 strong)\n- Does **NOT rule out** NF and must NOT delay surgery\n\nLethal trap: ordering imaging/awaiting LRINEC/giving antibiotics alone while patient deteriorates — **definitive treatment = URGENT surgical debridement**; mortality rises sharply with delay",
   "whatFirst": "- **Resuscitate** (sepsis: fluids, blood cultures) AND call surgery for **IMMEDIATE debridement** — diagnosis is surgical/clinical\n- Start **broad antibiotics** (eTG: meropenem or piperacillin-tazobactam) + **vancomycin** + add **clindamycin or lincomycin** for antitoxin (anti-exotoxin) effect\n- Do **NOT let CT/MRI delay theatre**",
   "discriminator": "- **Cellulitis**: pain matches appearance, slow, responds to antibiotics, no crepitus/bullae/systemic collapse\n- **NF**: pain >> signs, crepitus, bullae, skin anaesthesia, rapid spread, septic shock — **surgical not medical**",
