   "topic": "Phases of healing & timing — the 'wound is weakest' MCQ trap (why dehiscence peaks day 5-8)",
   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Phases of wound healing:\n- **Haemostasis** — immediate\n- **Inflammation** — day 0–~3 (neutrophils then macrophages)\n- **Proliferation** — day ~3–21 (fibroblasts, type III collagen, granulation, angiogenesis, epithelialisation)\n- **Remodelling/maturation** — week 3 to ~1 year (type III collagen replaced by type I, scar matures)\n\nKey gotcha:\n- Tensile strength is **LOWEST around day 5-7** (early proliferative phase — old collagen lysed, new collagen not yet cross-linked)\n  - Exactly when **abdominal dehiscence peaks**\n- Wound regains only **~20% strength at 3 weeks**\n- **Maximum of ~70-80%** of original strength ever — **never 100%**",
   "whatFirst": "- Tie the timing: suture/skin support matters most through the **proliferative phase**\n- A wound that fails around **day 5-8** is failing because that is its **weakest mechanical point**",
   "discriminator": "- **Type III collagen** laid down FIRST (proliferation)\n- Replaced by **type I** in remodelling\n- Wound at 1 week has **~3-5% strength**; never returns to **100%**",
   "redFlags": "- Sudden **serosanguineous ('pink/salmon') discharge** from an abdominal wound around day 5-8\n  - = **impending dehiscence** (fascial failure) until proven otherwise",
   "mcqTrap": "- Distractor: **'A healed scar regains full (100%) original tensile strength after 1 year'** — WRONG\n  - Ceiling is **~70-80%**",
   "mnemonic": "Healing order: Hi-Pro Race (Haemostasis, Inflammation, Proliferation, Remodelling). Collagen: 'III before I' (3 comes first then matures to 1).",
   "viva": "- Examiner probes: **'This abdominal wound burst on day 7 — why then?'**\n  - Answer: peak collagen turnover, **lowest tensile strength**",
   "source": "Standard surgical/physiology curriculum (RACS); collagen and tensile-strength figures stable/uncontested.",
