   "topic": "Primary vs secondary vs tertiary (delayed primary) wound closure — which heals when, and the MCQ trap",
   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Three types of wound healing intention:\n- **Primary intention** = edges apposed immediately (sutures/staples/glue) within hours\n  - Minimal granulation, fast, fine scar\n  - Used for **clean incised wounds**\n- **Secondary intention** = wound left **OPEN** to heal by granulation + contraction + re-epithelialisation from the base up\n  - Slow, large scar, more contracture\n  - Used for contaminated/infected wounds, large tissue-loss wounds, abscess cavities\n  - **NEVER surgically closed** — left to granulate completely\n- **Tertiary intention** = **DELAYED primary closure**\n  - Deliberately left open ~3-5 days (to control contamination/oedema/infection), then sutured closed once clean\n\nTempting wrong answer: calling a wound left open then closed later **'secondary intention'** — that is **tertiary**",
   "whatFirst": "Decide closure method by **contamination**:\n- Clean/clean-contaminated → **primary**\n- Grossly contaminated, infected, or significant tissue loss → **secondary**\n- Contaminated wound you intend to close after a delay → **tertiary** (delayed primary, day 3-5)",
   "discriminator": "- **Open-then-sutured = tertiary**, NOT secondary\n- **Secondary** = open until fully granulated, never re-sutured",
   "redFlags": "- A 'clean' wound being left to heal by **secondary intention** should prompt you to ask why\n  - (Suspected contamination/ischaemia)",
   "mcqTrap": "- Distractor: **'A traumatic wound debrided, left open for 4 days, then sutured heals by secondary intention'** — WRONG\n  - That is **tertiary/delayed primary intention**",
   "mnemonic": "Primary = Promptly closed; Secondary = Stays open (granulates); Tertiary = Tarry then close (delayed).",
   "viva": "- Examiner probes: **'Why leave this contaminated laceration open rather than closing it primarily?'**\n  - Answer: to avoid trapping infection → **delayed primary (tertiary) closure** once clean",
   "source": "Standard surgical principles (RACS curriculum; consistent with WHO Global Guidelines for the Prevention of SSI). Definitions stable/uncontested.",
