   "subarea": "Wound healing & SSI",
   "trap": "Definitions:\n- **Dehiscence** = separation of a surgical wound along its layers; may be superficial (skin) or full-thickness **fascial** (burst abdomen)\n- **Evisceration** = full-thickness dehiscence WITH **protrusion of abdominal viscera** through the wound — a surgical emergency\n\nClassic timing: abdominal fascial dehiscence peaks **DAY 5-8** post-op (lowest tensile strength)\n\nCardinal warning sign: sudden gush of **serosanguineous / 'salmon-pink' / 'pink watery' fluid** from the wound — precedes/heralds dehiscence\n\nTrap: students focus on antibiotics or reassurance when the answer is **theatre**\n\nRisk factors ('RACS failure' factors):\n- Raised **intra-abdominal pressure** (cough/ileus/obstruction)\n- Poor tissue: malnutrition, steroids, diabetes, jaundice, malignancy\n- Technical: closure tension/suture failure\n- **Infection**",
   "whatFirst": "If **evisceration**:\n- **Do NOT push viscera back in**\n- Lie patient flat with knees flexed\n- Cover bowel with **sterile saline-soaked gauze**\n- Keep **NBM**, IV access + fluids, analgesia\n- **Call surgeon/theatre urgently**\n- Broad-spectrum antibiotics\n\nIf **fascial dehiscence without evisceration**:\n- Still **urgent return to theatre** for resuture",
