   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "In a post-bowel-resection patient 'not quite right' around POD5-7:\n- FIRST: recognise subtle physiology — **persistent/new tachycardia and falling urine output** BEFORE frank peritonitis\n- Take bloods: **FBC, CRP, lactate, U&E**\n- Examine the abdomen\n- **Escalate to the surgical team** — do NOT wait for overt peritonism",
   "trap": "Classic timing: **POD5-7** (range 3-10)\n\nEarliest and most reliable signs:\n- **Unexplained persistent tachycardia** (HR that won't settle)\n- **Oliguria**\n  - These precede fever, pain and peritonitis\n\nKey CRP clue:\n- **CRP that fails to fall after POD3-4** is a key sign\n- CRP rise **>50 mg/L over 24h from POD3 = >96% specific** for leak\n\n'Failure to rally' / **prolonged ileus** + low-grade confusion in an elderly patient can be the only sign",
   "discriminator": "- **Persistent tachycardia + oliguria + CRP not falling POD5-7** after colorectal/upper GI anastomosis = **LEAK** until proven otherwise\n- Distinguish from simple **wound infection** (localised, well systemically)\n- Distinguish from **atrial fibrillation** (do an ECG — but new AF is often itself a leak/sepsis marker)\n- **CT abdomen/pelvis with contrast** (+/- water-soluble contrast study) = confirmatory test\n  - A **normal early CT does NOT exclude** anastomotic leak",
   "redFlags": "- **Tachycardia persisting despite fluids**, oliguria, rising lactate, peritonism, new AF, or septic shock\n- **ESCALATE**: re-laparotomy / source-control situation\n- Do **NOT discharge** a patient with unexplained tachycardia",
   "mcqTrap": "- Seductive WRONG answer: attribute POD6 tachycardia to **'pain', 'atelectasis' or 'dehydration'** and prescribe analgesia/fluids and observe\n  - Persistent tachycardia after bowel surgery = **leak**\n  - Correct step: **urgent senior review + contrast CT**, not reassurance",
   "mnemonic": "'Tachy that won't track down on day 6 = the join's let go.' Leak triad: Tachycardia, low Urine, rising CRP.",
   "viva": "- Examiner probes: **'Why won't you just give this POD6 patient with HR 110 some morphine and IV fluids?'**\n  - Articulate: unexplained persistent tachycardia = **earliest sign of anastomotic leak**\n  - Then **ISBAR escalation** to registrar\n  - Need for **contrast CT** and **source control**\n  - Consent angle: **re-laparotomy / possible stoma**",
   "visualHtml": "<div class=\"gv-flow\"><div class=\"gv-step\">POD5-7 post-bowel resection, patient 'off'</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Check: persistent tachycardia, urine output, CRP trend, lactate</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Tachycardia + oliguria + CRP not falling = suspect LEAK</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Senior review + CT abdo/pelvis with contrast</div><div class=\"gv-step\">Resuscitate + antibiotics + source control (drain / re-laparotomy +/- stoma)</div></div>",
   "source": "POD5-7 timing and tachycardia/oliguria/failure-to-rally presentation per colorectal surgical literature (Dove OAS; ITACS leak study). CRP rise >50 mg/L/24h from POD3 = >96% specific per PMC6997159. Australian antimicrobial framing per Therapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotic (eTG, current).",
