   "topic": "Ileus vs mechanical bowel obstruction — the post-op 'still not opening bowels' call",
   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "- Distinguish physiological from pathological FIRST by **the clock and the bowel sounds**\n- Normal post-op ileus resolves by **~POD3**\n  - Small bowel <24h, stomach 24-48h, **colon 48-72h**\n- **Prolonged/paralytic ileus** = failure of bowel function to return by POD3-5 with NO mechanical cause\n- Management:\n  - Examine for distension, listen (absent/quiet = ileus; high-pitched tinkling = obstruction)\n  - Keep **NBM**, NG tube if vomiting/distended\n  - **Correct electrolytes**, stop opioids/anticholinergics\n  - Image with **CT if not resolving**",
   "trap": "**TIMING**: investigate persistent ileus beyond **POD3-5**\n\nKey discriminator on CT:\n- **Mechanical obstruction** = **TRANSITION POINT** (dilated proximal, collapsed distal bowel)\n- **Ileus** = **diffuse/uniform dilatation** with air-fluid levels and NO transition point\n  - CT distinguishes the two with very high accuracy for complete mechanical SBO\n\nBowel sounds:\n- **Absent/silent** = ileus\n- **High-pitched/tinkling + colicky pain + early vomiting** = mechanical obstruction",
   "discriminator": "- **Ileus** = silent abdomen, generalised gradual distension, less colicky pain, reversible precipitants\n  - (Opioids, **hypokalaemia/hypomagnesaemia**, hypothyroid, immobility)\n- **Mechanical** (often adhesional early post-op) = colicky pain, tinkling sounds, vomiting, transition point on CT\n\nDangerous overlap — **CLOSED-LOOP / strangulating obstruction**:\n- **Constant** (not colicky) pain, tachycardia, raised lactate, peritonism\n- = **surgical emergency**",
   "redFlags": "- **Constant severe pain**, tachycardia, fever, rising lactate, peritonism, or CT signs of ischaemia/closed loop\n  - = **Strangulation → theatre**\n- **Faeculent vomiting**\n- **Massively distended caecum (>9-12 cm)** risks perforation",
   "mcqTrap": "- Tempting WRONG answer: take an early post-op 'obstruction' **straight to theatre**\n  - Most EARLY post-op small-bowel obstruction is **adhesional/inflammatory** and settles with conservative management\n  - (NBM, NG decompression, IV fluids, correct electrolytes) UNLESS **strangulation red flags** present\n- Opposite trap: **mislabelling true mechanical obstruction as 'ileus'** and just waiting\n  - CT **transition point** settles it",
   "mnemonic": "'Silent & even = ileus; tinkling with a transition = obstruction.' Fix the 4 reversibles for ileus: Opioids, Potassium/Magnesium, Mobility, Sepsis.",
   "viva": "- Examiner: **'POD4, distended, vomiting, not passing flatus — ileus or obstruction, and how do you tell?'**\n  - Give the **bowel-sound contrast**, the reversible precipitants of ileus\n  - CT **transition point** as the discriminator\n  - State **conservative-first** for early adhesional SBO\n  - State the **strangulation red flags** that mandate theatre\n  - ISBAR + **consent for laparotomy** if strangulating",
   "visualHtml": "<table class=\"gv-table\"><thead><tr><th></th><th>Paralytic ileus</th><th>Mechanical obstruction</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Pain</td><td>Mild, generalised</td><td>Colicky (constant = strangulation)</td></tr><tr><td>Bowel sounds</td><td>Absent / quiet</td><td>High-pitched, tinkling</td></tr><tr><td>CT</td><td>Diffuse dilatation, no transition</td><td>TRANSITION POINT, distal collapse</td></tr><tr><td>Cause</td><td>Opioids, low K+/Mg2+, immobility, sepsis</td><td>Adhesions, hernia, mass</td></tr><tr><td>First Rx</td><td>NBM, NG, correct electrolytes, stop opioids</td><td>Conservative if early/adhesional; theatre if strangulating</td></tr></tbody></table>",
   "source": "Normal GI recovery times and prolonged-ileus >POD3-5 threshold per StatPearls Postoperative Ileus. CT transition point discriminator per AJR (Frager) and ileus/SBO reviews. Conservative-first for early adhesional SBO per surgical standard.",
