   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "- **ABCDE + SpO2** on room air, RR, HR, temp, and focused chest exam FIRST\n- **Sit the patient up**, give **controlled oxygen** if hypoxic\n- Get **ECG and CXR**, and **ABG/VBG** if significant hypoxia\n- The **POD and vitals pattern** then steer you to the diagnosis",
   "trap": "- **Timing split** is the key discriminator:\n  - **Atelectasis**: **POD1–2** — most common early cause; basal crackles, mild desaturation, responds to mobilisation/spirometry\n  - **Pneumonia**: **POD3–5** — productive cough, focal signs, consolidation on CXR, raised WCC/CRP\n  - **PE**: **POD5+** and can be any day — sudden pleuritic pain, tachycardia, hypoxia with a **clear chest** and often a **normal/near-normal CXR**\n- The **'clear chest + hypoxia + tachycardia'** combination is the **PE giveaway**",
   "discriminator": "- **PE vs atelectasis/pneumonia**: PE has hypoxia **out of proportion** to chest findings and an **unremarkable CXR**; atelectasis/pneumonia have **abnormal CXR**\n- Use the **two-tier Wells score**:\n  - **'PE unlikely' (<=4)** → D-dimer\n    - Post-op D-dimer is **unhelpfully raised**; only a low-probability + **negative D-dimer** is reassuring\n  - **'PE likely' (>4)** → straight to **CTPA**\n- **CTPA** sensitivity **~96–100%**, specificity **~89–98%**",
   "redFlags": "- **Sudden collapse**, hypotension, syncope = massive PE\n- **RV strain on ECG**: S1Q3T3, new RBBB\n- Sustained **SpO2 fall** → consider **thrombolysis**\n- **Rising O2 requirement** despite physio\n- **Confusion/exhaustion** = impending respiratory failure",
   "mcqTrap": "- Trap: POD5 sudden breathlessness with a **normal CXR** — tempting wrong answer is 'reassure, this is atelectasis' or 'repeat CXR'\n  - Clear CXR + hypoxia + tachycardia after surgery = **PE → CTPA**, not reassurance\n- Conversely, treating an obvious **POD1 atelectasis with antibiotics** is the over-treatment trap",
   "mnemonic": "'1-2 collapse-y lung (atelectasis), 3-5 the lung gets gunky (pneumonia), 5+ a clot that's sneaky (PE).' Clear chest + hypoxia = clot.",
   "viva": "- Examiner: '**POD5**, sudden SOB, sats 90%, chest clear, CXR normal — what next and why?'\n  - Name **PE**, justify with the **clear-chest-disproportionate-hypoxia** logic\n  - Apply **Wells score** → go to **CTPA**\n  - Note: **post-op D-dimer is near-useless**\n  - **ISBAR escalate**\n  - Be ready for consent/risk angle if **anticoagulating or thrombolysing**",
   "visualHtml": "<table class=\"gv-table\"><thead><tr><th></th><th>Atelectasis</th><th>Pneumonia</th><th>PE</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Day</td><td>POD 1-2</td><td>POD 3-5</td><td>POD 5+ (any)</td></tr><tr><td>Chest exam</td><td>Basal crackles</td><td>Focal, bronchial</td><td>Often CLEAR</td></tr><tr><td>CXR</td><td>Basal collapse</td><td>Consolidation</td><td>Normal / near-normal</td></tr><tr><td>Key sign</td><td>Mild desat, mobilises away</td><td>Sputum, raised CRP/WCC</td><td>Hypoxia out of proportion, pleuritic, tachy</td></tr><tr><td>Test/Rx</td><td>Spirometry, physio</td><td>CXR, antibiotics (eTG)</td><td>Wells -> CTPA, anticoagulate</td></tr></tbody></table>",
   "source": "POD timing per postoperative pulmonary complications literature (StatPearls; PMC reviews). Two-tier Wells >4 = 'PE likely' -> CTPA per MDCalc/Wells validation. Pneumonia antibiotic choice per Therapeutic Guidelines: Antibiotic (eTG, current).",
