   "topic": "Post-op fever by day — the 5 Ws timeline (when the day points the finger)",
   "subarea": "Post-operative complications",
   "whatFirst": "- **Don't reflexively septic-screen** every post-op fever\n- The **POD narrows the cause** before you investigate\n- **Examine**: wound + legs + IV/cannula sites + catheter + chest\n- A **self-limiting fever in the first 24–48h** after a big op is usually the **inflammatory stress response**, NOT infection",
   "trap": "- **Exact 5 Ws timeline**:\n  - **Wind** (pneumonia/aspiration/PE; atelectasis often blamed but is **NOT** a true independent fever cause): **POD1–2** (earliest)\n  - **Water** (UTI, often catheter-associated): **POD3–5**\n  - **Wound** (surgical site infection): **POD5–7**\n  - **Walking** (DVT/PE): **POD5+**, persists for weeks\n  - **Wonder drugs/Weird** (drug fever, transfusion reaction, line/abscess, anastomotic leak): **any time**, especially POD5–7+\n- **IMMEDIATE fever (<6h)** with erythematous/painful/**crepitant wound** = **necrotising soft-tissue infection** or Group A strep/clostridial — **surgical emergency**, NOT routine SSI",
   "discriminator": "- **POD1 low-grade fever** + clear chest + clear urine after major abdo/thoracic = **post-op inflammatory response/early atelectasis**\n  - Action: mobilise/incentive spirometry, **NOT antibiotics** — atelectasis is not proven to cause fever and is the most over-treated 'cause'\n- **Fever first appearing POD5–7** with rising tachycardia + abdominal signs after bowel surgery = think **anastomotic leak**, not 'just a wound infection'",
   "redFlags": "- Fever **<6h post-op** with disproportionate wound pain, crepitus, or **grey/dishwater discharge** = **necrotising soft-tissue infection → theatre**\n- Fever + **hypotension + new confusion** = **sepsis**, escalate\n- Fever + breathlessness + pleuritic pain **POD5+** = **PE**",
   "mcqTrap": "- Tempting wrong answer: **'start empirical broad-spectrum antibiotics'** for an isolated POD1 low-grade fever with a clear septic screen\n  - This is the **inflammatory response/atelectasis**; answer is **chest physio/mobilisation**\n  - Antibiotics here are the **distractor**",
   "mnemonic": "5 Ws in day order: Wind (1-2) -> Water (3-5) -> Wound (5-7) -> Walking/veins (5+) -> Wonder drugs/Weird (anytime). 'Wind blows first, the Wound shows late.'",
   "viva": "- Examiner: '**POD2 spike to 38.2**, what first?'\n  - Targeted exam (chest, wound, legs, lines, catheter) + the **day-based differential**, NOT a blind pan-culture\n  - Then **ISBAR** if unwell\n  - Justify why you would **NOT give antibiotics** for an isolated early low-grade fever",
   "visualHtml": "<table class=\"gv-table\"><thead><tr><th>POD</th><th>W</th><th>Cause</th><th>Action</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>1-2</td><td>Wind</td><td>Pneumonia/aspiration (atelectasis blamed)</td><td>Mobilise, spirometry, CXR if persists</td></tr><tr><td>3-5</td><td>Water</td><td>UTI (catheter)</td><td>Urinalysis/culture, remove IDC if able</td></tr><tr><td>5-7</td><td>Wound</td><td>SSI +/- deep collection</td><td>Inspect, swab, consider CT for abscess/leak</td></tr><tr><td>5+</td><td>Walking</td><td>DVT / PE</td><td>Doppler / CTPA, Wells</td></tr><tr><td>Any</td><td>Wonder drugs</td><td>Drug fever, transfusion, line sepsis</td><td>Review meds/lines, cultures</td></tr></tbody></table>",
